    <item>
      <title>Bias</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/bias/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/bias/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Bias in statistics is a systematic error that causes estimates to deviate from the true &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/population/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;population&lt;/a&gt; parameter in a consistent direction. An estimator is biased if its expected value differs from the parameter it estimates: Bias(θ̂) = E[θ̂] − θ. A biased estimator consistently overestimates or underestimates, regardless of &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/sample/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;sample&lt;/a&gt; size.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Bias enters at multiple stages. Sampling bias occurs when the sample does not represent the population (self-selection, convenience sampling, survivorship bias). Measurement bias occurs when the measurement process systematically distorts values. Estimation bias occurs when the statistical method itself introduces systematic error — using n rather than n − 1 in the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/variance/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;variance&lt;/a&gt; formula, for example, produces a biased estimator.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Conditional Probability</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/conditional-probability/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/conditional-probability/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Conditional probability is the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/probability/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;probability&lt;/a&gt; of one &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/event/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;event&lt;/a&gt; given that another event has already occurred or is known to be true. It answers questions like: what is the probability it will rain tomorrow, &lt;em&gt;given&lt;/em&gt; that the barometric pressure is falling? What is the probability a patient has a disease, &lt;em&gt;given&lt;/em&gt; that their test came back positive? The &amp;ldquo;given&amp;rdquo; clause changes the calculation by restricting attention to a subset of the possible outcomes.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Distribution</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/distribution/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/distribution/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A distribution describes the complete pattern of how a random variable&amp;rsquo;s values are spread out — which values are possible and how probable each one is. It is the full picture of uncertainty about a quantity, rather than a single summary like the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/mean/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;mean&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/median/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;median&lt;/a&gt;. Two datasets can have the same mean and very different distributions: the scores {50, 50, 50} and {0, 50, 100} both average to 50, but the distributions tell completely different stories about what to expect.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Event</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/event/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/event/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;An event is a collection of outcomes from a probabilistic experiment — something that either happens or does not happen, and to which a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/probability/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;probability&lt;/a&gt; can be assigned. When you roll a die, &amp;ldquo;rolling an even number&amp;rdquo; is an event: it is the set of outcomes &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;4&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;6&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\{2, 4, 6\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; within the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/sample-space/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;sample space&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;4&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;6&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Omega = \{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. &amp;ldquo;Rolling a 3&amp;rdquo; is an event (the set &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\{3\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;). &amp;ldquo;Rolling a number less than 10&amp;rdquo; is an event (the entire sample space — it always happens). &amp;ldquo;Rolling a 7&amp;rdquo; is an event too (the empty set — it never happens).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Independence</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/independence/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/independence/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Two &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/event/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;events&lt;/a&gt; are independent if knowing that one occurred tells you nothing about whether the other occurred. You flip a fair coin twice: whether the first flip lands heads is independent of whether the second lands heads — the coin has no memory. You draw a card from a deck, replace it, shuffle, and draw again: the two draws are independent. But draw without replacing: now the draws are dependent, because the first draw changes what remains in the deck.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Likelihood</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/likelihood/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/likelihood/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The likelihood of a hypothesis given observed data is the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/probability/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;probability&lt;/a&gt; of having observed that data if the hypothesis were true. It asks: how well does this hypothesis explain what we actually saw? If a coin is fair (hypothesis: &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0.5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p = 0.5&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;), the probability of observing 8 heads in 10 flips is about 0.044. If the coin is biased (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0.8&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p = 0.8&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;), the probability of that same outcome is about 0.302. The biased-coin hypothesis has higher likelihood — it makes the observed data more probable.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Mean</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/mean/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/mean/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The arithmetic mean of a collection of values is their sum divided by their count: given values &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;…&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, the mean is &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mover accent=&#34;true&#34;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;ˉ&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mover&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋯&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;/&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\bar{x} = (x_1 + x_2 + \cdots + x_n) / n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. If five students score 70, 80, 85, 90, and 100 on a test, the mean is &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;70&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;80&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;85&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;90&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;100&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;/&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;85&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;(70 + 80 + 85 + 90 + 100) / 5 = 85&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The mean answers &amp;ldquo;what is the typical value?&amp;rdquo; by giving every observation equal weight — each score pulls the mean toward itself by the same amount per unit.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Median</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/median/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/median/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The median of a collection of values is the middle value when all values are arranged in order. Half the values fall below the median and half above — it splits the data into two equal halves. If you have five test scores (70, 80, 85, 90, 100), the median is 85, the third value. If you have six scores (70, 80, 85, 90, 95, 100), the median is the average of the third and fourth values: &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;85&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;90&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;/&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;87.5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;(85 + 90)/2 = 87.5&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Mode</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/mode/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/mode/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The mode of a dataset is the value that appears most often. In the dataset {3, 5, 5, 7, 8, 5, 9}, the mode is 5 — it occurs three times, more than any other value. A dataset can have one mode (unimodal), two modes (bimodal), several modes (multimodal), or no mode at all (when every value occurs equally often).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The mode is the simplest of the three classical measures of central tendency (alongside the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/mean/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;mean&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/median/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;median&lt;/a&gt;), and the only one that applies to categorical data. You cannot compute the mean or median of a collection of colors, but the most frequent color is perfectly well defined. If a shoe store sells more size-10 shoes than any other size, size 10 is the modal shoe size — a practically useful fact even though &amp;ldquo;average shoe size&amp;rdquo; might be 9.7, a size that does not exist.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Population</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/population/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/population/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A population is the complete &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/sets/terms/set/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;set&lt;/a&gt; of individuals, items, or observations that a statistical study aims to describe. It is the thing you actually want to know about — the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/sample/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;sample&lt;/a&gt; is just the means by which you learn. If a medical researcher wants to know whether a drug lowers blood pressure in adults, the population is all adults (or perhaps all adults with hypertension, depending on the research question). If a manufacturer wants to know the defect rate of its products, the population is every item produced.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Posterior</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/posterior/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/posterior/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The posterior is what you believe after seeing the evidence. It is a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/probability/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;probability&lt;/a&gt; distribution &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∣&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;P(H \mid E)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; over hypotheses &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;H&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, updated from a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/prior/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;prior&lt;/a&gt; distribution &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;P(H)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in light of observed evidence &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;E&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, using Bayes&amp;rsquo; theorem: &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∣&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∣&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋅&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;/&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;P(H \mid E) = P(E \mid H) \cdot P(H) / P(E)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The prior captures what you believed before seeing data. The &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/likelihood/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;likelihood&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∣&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;P(E \mid H)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; captures how well each hypothesis explains the data. The posterior combines both into a single distribution that reflects everything you know.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Prior</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/prior/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/prior/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A prior is a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/probability/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;probability&lt;/a&gt; distribution that represents what you believe about a hypothesis before seeing any evidence. It is the starting point of Bayesian inference — the baseline against which new data are weighed. If you are estimating the bias of a coin, the prior encodes your initial uncertainty: maybe you believe the coin is probably fair (prior concentrated near &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0.5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p = 0.5&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;), or maybe you know nothing and consider all values equally plausible (uniform prior over &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;[&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;]&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;[0, 1]&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Probability</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/probability/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/probability/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Probability is a way of assigning numbers to uncertain outcomes so that the numbers behave consistently. You flip a coin: you do not know whether it will land heads, but you can say the chance is &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;/&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;1/2&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. You roll a die: the chance of any particular face is &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;/&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;6&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;1/6&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Probability gives these intuitions a precise mathematical form.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The modern formalization rests on three axioms laid down by Andrey Nikolaevich Kolmogorov in &lt;em&gt;Grundbegriffe der Wahrscheinlichkeitsrechnung&lt;/em&gt; (1933). Start with a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/sample-space/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;sample space&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Omega&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; — the set of all possible outcomes. Certain subsets of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Omega&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; are designated as &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/event/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;events&lt;/a&gt; (technically, they form a σ-algebra). A probability is a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/terms/function/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;function&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;P&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that assigns a number to each event, satisfying: (1) &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≥&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;P(A) \geq 0&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; for every event &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;; (2) &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;P(\Omega) = 1&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;; and (3) if &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;…&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A_1, A_2, \ldots&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; are mutually exclusive events, then &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∪&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∪&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋯&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋯&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;P(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup \cdots) = P(A_1) + P(A_2) + \cdots&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Everything else in probability theory — &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/conditional-probability/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;conditional probability&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/independence/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;independence&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/distribution/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;distributions&lt;/a&gt;, the law of large numbers, the central limit theorem — follows from these three axioms.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Sample</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/sample/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/sample/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A sample is a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/sets/terms/subset/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;subset&lt;/a&gt; of a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/population/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;population&lt;/a&gt; selected for observation. Statistics exists because populations are usually too large, too expensive, or too impractical to observe in full. You cannot measure the blood pressure of every human alive, but you can measure the blood pressure of 500 people and use the results to draw conclusions about the whole. The 500 people are the sample; the conclusions about all humans are the inference.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Sample Space</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/sample-space/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/sample-space/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The sample space is the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/sets/terms/set/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;set&lt;/a&gt; of all possible outcomes of a probabilistic experiment — everything that could happen, listed exhaustively. For a coin flip, the sample space is &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;heads&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;tails&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Omega = \{\text{heads}, \text{tails}\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. For rolling a standard die, &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;4&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;6&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Omega = \{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. For measuring the temperature outside right now, &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Omega&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; might be the real numbers, or more realistically some interval like &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;[&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;−&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;50&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;60&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;]&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;[-50, 60]&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; degrees Celsius. The sample space is the universe within which probability operates: everything that receives a probability must be expressible in terms of outcomes from &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Omega&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Standard Deviation</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/standard-deviation/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/standard-deviation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The standard deviation measures how spread out a collection of values is from its &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/mean/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;mean&lt;/a&gt;. It answers the question: on average, how far do individual observations fall from the center? A standard deviation of 0 means every value is identical — there is no spread at all. A small standard deviation means values cluster tightly around the mean. A large standard deviation means values are widely dispersed.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Consider two classes of students who both average 80 on a test. In one class, every student scores between 75 and 85 — the standard deviation is small (around 3). In the other, scores range from 40 to 100 — the standard deviation is large (around 20). The mean tells you the center; the standard deviation tells you how much the data scatter around that center.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Variable</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/variable/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/variable/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A variable is a measurable &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/philosophy/terms/property/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;property&lt;/a&gt; that can take different values across individuals or observations. Height, temperature, color, and income are all variables. In statistics, variables are classified by their type: a quantitative variable takes numerical values (continuous like height, or discrete like count), while a categorical variable takes labels (nominal like color, or ordinal like rating).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A random variable is the formal mathematical version: a &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/terms/function/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;function&lt;/a&gt; X: Ω → ℝ (or more generally, to some measurable space) from the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/sample-space/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;sample space&lt;/a&gt; to a set of values. The random variable assigns a numerical value to each outcome, allowing probabilistic analysis. The &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/distribution/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;distribution&lt;/a&gt; of a random variable describes how its values are spread — summarized by &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/mean/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;mean&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/variance/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;variance&lt;/a&gt;, and other measures.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Variance</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/variance/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/variance/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The variance of a collection of values is the average squared deviation from the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/mean/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;mean&lt;/a&gt;: Var(X) = (1/n) Σ (xᵢ − x̄)². It measures how spread out the values are — a variance of 0 means all values are identical, and larger variance means greater spread. The sample variance typically uses n − 1 in the denominator (Bessel&amp;rsquo;s correction) to produce an unbiased estimator of the &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/population/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;population&lt;/a&gt; variance.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Variance is measured in squared units of the original data, which can be hard to interpret directly. The &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/standard-deviation/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;standard deviation&lt;/a&gt; σ = √Var(X) returns to the original units and is the more commonly reported measure of spread. For a normal &lt;a href=&#34;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/probability/terms/distribution/&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;distribution&lt;/a&gt;, about 68% of values fall within one standard deviation of the mean and about 95% within two.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
  </channel>
